    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-09-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-09-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="610"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d610">
                <head>610. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the Executive
                    Secretary of the Department of State (<persName corresp="#p_RBH1" type="to"
                        >Read</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d610fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, S/S–<gloss target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> Files: Lot 72
                        D 316, <gloss target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> 295. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-09-02">September 2, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>US Policy Toward South Africa—Status Report on <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                            >NSAM</gloss> 295</item>
                </list>
                <p>The July 31, 1965 Status Report on <gloss target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> 295<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d610fn2">
                        <ref target="#d609">Document 609</ref>.</note> raises some questions which
                    deserve a close look.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Would US policy objectives be furthered if we were to enlist the support
                        of friendly countries with diplomatic representation in South Africa to join
                        in US–<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> approaches to the South African
                        Government on apartheid and the South West Africa case?</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Is there any political advantage to be gained for the US and its policy
                        objectives by transferring our space tracking facilities in South Africa
                        before events force us to do so?</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">R. W. Komer</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
